    <summary type="text">In &#8220;Sunny Side Up,&#8217;&#8217; artist Eran Shakine pokes fun at lofty notions about art, inspiration, and genius. In the text below his sketch of a museum scene, Shakine notes that museum-goers spend an average of 10 seconds with each work, half of which is spent reading the label. He draws a hairpiece in the shape of, say, a Frank Gehry building and plops it on Gehry&#8217;s head. With a few bold lines, Shakine creates a world of commentary.</summary>
    <content type="xhtml">
      <p>In &#8220;Sunny Side Up&#8217;&#8217; (Hirmer), artist Eran Shakine, who lives in Tel Aviv and London, pokes fun at lofty notions about art, inspiration, and genius. In the text below his sketch of a museum scene, Shakine notes that museumgoers spend an average of 10 seconds with each work, half of which is spent reading the label. He draws a hairpiece in the shape of, say, a Frank Gehry building and plops it on Gehry&#8217;s head. He dresses Ralph Lauren and other male fashion designers in the clothing they create for women. With a few bold lines, Shakine creates a world of commentary.</p>
    </content>
